06234nam a22007695i 9781442632738DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161967onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426327387 a10.3138/97814426327382doi  a(DE-B1597)465735  a(OCoLC)979756803  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aLB1026b.B87 1967eb 7aEDU0340002bisacsh04a375.00971322300aNew Designs for Learning :bHighlights of the Reports of the Ontario Curriculum Institute, 1963-1966 /ced. by Brian Burnham. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©1967  a1 online resource (354 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tEditor's Note -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. The Curriculum and The Functions of The School -- tIntroduction -- tSocial and Individual Aspects of the Curriculum -- tFor Whom We Teach -- tA Curriculum Credo -- tPart Two. New Curricula -- tIntroduction -- tReading -- tScience -- tMathematics -- tModern Languages -- tThe Humanities and The Social Sciences -- tPart Three. New Technology and The Curriculum -- tIntroduction -- tOverview -- tTeaching Materials in the Reading Programme -- tPart Four. Evaluating New Curricula -- tIntroduction -- tEvaluating the Curriculum -- tEvaluation in the Reading Programme -- tPart Five. Curriculum Research -- tIntroduction -- tSuggested Research Topics -- tNeeded Curriculum Research -- tPart Six. New Designs for Learning -- tIntroduction -- tCurriculum Change -- tInstructional Trends in the United States -- tA New Model For Educational Research and Development -- tGovernors of The Ontario Curriculum Institute, 1963 - 19660 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe last twenty-five years have seen unprecedented growth in the application of science in critical areas of human endeavor. Explosive acceleration in the rate of growth of learning has created unquestioned benefits but it has also served as a catalyst for social, economic, and political changes of a disturbing nature. Too often there has not been time enough to assimilate the new learning or to reach agreement on the use of powerful new technologies.How have educators responded to the need to prepare young people to live with, create, and control change? In Ontario the response was unique and dramatic. Teachers and academics, school trustees, administrators, and inspectors as well as the provincial government and private philanthropy came together to create the Ontario Curriculum Institute, chartered as a non-profit organization in January 1963. Its objectives were to study all phases of the curriculum in the schools and universities of Ontario and to disseminate the results of their research and developmental work. Studies of course content, of learning processes and instructional methodology, of school and classroom organization were launched and new learning resources, experimental programs, and demonstration classrooms were designed and executed. Findings filled seventeen small volumes to September 1966 after which the reports of the study committees were issued by the Ontario Institute for Studies in Education with which the Curriculum Institute had merged.In New Designs for Learning (which can be considered a sequel to Design for Learning, edited by Northrop Frye, University of Toronto Press, 1962) extracts from all seventeen reports, many now out-of-print, have been organized to deal with the most pressing and interesting aspects of educational reform. Selections were also chosen to provide for educator and layman alike the broadest possible grounds for assessment of the Institute’s work. Discerning introductions which set the book and its individual chapters clearly in the mainstream of the curriculum reform movement have been provided by the editor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  